# Tests must fail without the fix

## Rule

A regression test is only useful if it fails on the broken implementation and
passes on the fixed implementation.

## Checklist

1. Name the exact regression the test protects.
2. Identify the assertion that would fail if the fix were reverted.
3. Include the boundary condition, not only the happy path.
4. For async behavior, assert final state after all relevant promises, timers,
   queues, events, or subscriptions settle.
5. For order-sensitive behavior, assert order explicitly.
6. For permissions, test allowed and denied paths.
7. For migrations or schema changes, test old/new compatibility when practical.
8. Avoid test-only implementation changes that make production code pass by
   accident.

## Pre-commit check

- [ ] Mentally reverting the fix makes the test fail.
- [ ] Test asserts the user-visible or persisted outcome.
- [ ] Test does not merely assert that a mock was called.
- [ ] Test cleanup restores globals, env vars, timers, and module state.
